Caesar Research Group PeopleWeave Project

Overview

The Caesar Research Group PeopleWeave Project provides a way for researchers to collaborate with one another. It connects researchers and allows for research scholars to see the university affiliation and research topics that their peers are completing research in. This is a project that is led by Professor Matthew Caesar and there are several teams involved: Recommendations, Knowledge Graph, etc.



I am a part of the Graph Visualizations team which means that my primary focus was enhancing the features of the interactive graph that provides a visual understanding of the network between researchers.

Our user lands on this page that appears like a search engine. They will be able to search for a researcher by name or university.



In order to make searches more efficient, I was able to implement an autocomplete feature. This autocomplete feature also accounts for first name and last name, ensuring that if a user is not certain about the full name of a researcher, they will still be able to find what they are looking for.





Upon completing a search, the user is redirected to a second page that provides more details. They will be able to view all professors that meet the search as well paper topics covered by these professors.

The graph on the right displays the network between these researchers. Each node is a researcher and any connected nodes indicate collaborations.



A completed search will update the starting node by highlighting it on the graph. This makes it easier for the user to identify the searched researcher and any of his or her collaborations.





Hovering over a node on the graph will give a quick glance of what their university affiliation is and what research topics they study.
